% ============================================================================
\section{Immunology of Renal Cell Carcinoma}
\label{sec:bg_immunology}
% ============================================================================

The immune system's response to cancer involves both innate and adaptive arms. The model includes six T cell types (CD8+ CTLs, CD8+ naive, CD4+ naive, Th1, Th2, Tregs), antigen-presenting cells (dendritic cells and plasmacytoid DCs), macrophages (M1 pro-inflammatory and M2 anti-inflammatory), natural killer cells, mast cells, and neutrophils.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Immune cell types and primary functions in the RCC model}
\label{tab:immune_cells}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
\textbf{Cell Type} & \textbf{Primary Function} \\
\midrule
CD8+ Cytotoxic T Cell & Direct tumor cell killing \\
CD8+ Naive T Cell & CTL precursor, requires activation \\
CD4+ Naive T Cell & Helper/Treg precursor \\
Th1 Helper T Cell & Pro-inflammatory, immune activation \\
Th2 Helper T Cell & Anti-inflammatory, mild immune suppression \\
Regulatory T Cell & Immunosuppression, tumor protection \\
Dendritic Cell & Antigen presentation, T cell activation \\
Plasmacytoid DC & Specialized antigen presentation, NK spawning \\
M1 Macrophage & Pro-inflammatory, tumor killing \\
M2 Macrophage & Anti-inflammatory, tumor promotion \\
Natural Killer Cell & Innate tumor recognition and killing \\
Mast Cell & Context-dependent pro/anti-tumor effects \\
Neutrophil & Population marker (minimal active behavior) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Immune checkpoints are inhibitory pathways that prevent autoimmunity but are co-opted by tumors for immune evasion. The PD-1/PD-L1 axis is most clinically relevant in RCC: PD-L1 expression on tumor cells binds PD-1 on T cells, delivering inhibitory signals that reduce T cell proliferation and cytotoxic activity.

% ============================================================================
\section{Tumor Metabolism}
\label{sec:bg_metabolism}
% ============================================================================

Otto Warburg observed that cancer cells preferentially metabolize glucose through glycolysis rather than oxidative phosphorylation, even with adequate oxygen---the Warburg effect~\cite{liberti2016}. While less efficient for ATP yield, glycolysis provides faster ATP production, biosynthetic precursors for proliferation, and microenvironment acidification that inhibits immune function. This creates metabolic competition between tumor cells and immune cells for limited glucose, with activated T cells becoming heavily dependent on glycolysis for effector functions. When glucose is scarce, T cell proliferation, cytokine production, and cytotoxic capacity are impaired, creating positive feedback favoring tumor expansion.

% ============================================================================
\section{Treatment Modalities}
\label{sec:bg_treatments}
% ============================================================================

Immune checkpoint inhibitors (ICIs) target the PD-1/PD-L1 signaling axis that tumors exploit to evade immune surveillance. Under physiological conditions, PD-L1 expressed on tumor cells engages the PD-1 receptor on T cells, delivering an inhibitory signal that suppresses proliferation and cytotoxic activity. ICI antibodies bind to either PD-1 or PD-L1, physically blocking this interaction and thereby restoring T cell effector function. The resulting reactivation of tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes leads to enhanced immune infiltration of the tumor mass, as functional T cells proliferate and recruit additional immune effectors to the tumor site~\cite{pardoll2012, ribas2018}.

Tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKIs) target VEGF receptor signaling to suppress the aberrant angiogenesis that sustains tumor growth. In RCC, the von Hippel--Lindau (VHL) tumor suppressor gene is frequently inactivated, leading to constitutive upregulation of VEGF and hypervascularization of the tumor. TKI agents such as axitinib and sunitinib block VEGF receptor tyrosine kinases, inhibiting new blood vessel formation and thereby restricting the nutrient supply available to proliferating tumor cells. Beyond their anti-angiogenic effects, TKIs induce tumor cell apoptosis, which releases neoantigens into the microenvironment and can prime dendritic cells for subsequent adaptive immune activation.

Combination ICI+TKI therapy has emerged as the standard first-line treatment for advanced RCC, motivated by a synergistic rationale that exploits the complementary mechanisms of the two drug classes. TKI-mediated vascular normalization improves the physical access of immune cells to the tumor interior, while the immunogenic cell death induced by TKIs releases neoantigens that can be processed and presented by dendritic cells. Concurrently, ICI removes the PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitory brake, ensuring that the T cells activated by these neoantigens retain their cytotoxic capacity. Pivotal clinical trials, including KEYNOTE-426~\cite{rini2019} and JAVELIN Renal 101~\cite{motzer2019}, demonstrated the superiority of combination therapy over monotherapy in terms of overall survival and progression-free survival. The ARON-1 study~\cite{santoni2024} extends this line of investigation by examining whether the optimal treatment strategy depends on patient sex, motivated by evidence that differential sex hormone modulation of both tumor biology and immune function may influence treatment response.

% ============================================================================
\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related_work}
% ============================================================================

A substantial body of computational work addresses the modeling of tumor growth, immune response, and treatment dynamics. This section surveys the principal modeling paradigms that have been applied to these problems, reviews the most relevant software frameworks and agent-based cancer models, and positions the present work relative to its direct predecessor.

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Continuum and PDE-Based Tumor Models}
\label{subsec:rw_continuum}
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

The classical approach to mathematical oncology relies on systems of ordinary or partial differential equations (ODEs/PDEs) to describe tumor growth as a continuum process. Benzekry et al.\ \cite{benzekry2014} provided a systematic comparison of several standard growth laws---exponential, logistic, Gompertz, and power-law---fitted to experimental tumor volume data across multiple cancer types. Their analysis demonstrated that while such models can reproduce aggregate growth curves with reasonable fidelity, they treat the tumor as a homogeneous mass characterized by a small number of scalar quantities. This abstraction necessarily discards information about intratumoral heterogeneity, spatial gradients, and stochastic cell-level events, all of which have been shown to influence treatment outcomes.

Macklin et al.\ \cite{macklin2012} advanced the continuum paradigm by coupling reaction-diffusion equations for nutrient transport with mechanical models of tissue deformation, enabling simulation of tumor morphology in a spatially resolved manner. Their framework captured macroscopic features such as necrotic core formation and invasive front dynamics. However, the continuum representation still averages over individual cell states, making it difficult to incorporate phenomena that arise from discrete cell-level heterogeneity---for example, the coexistence of immunogenic and immune-evasive tumor subclones within the same lesion, or the stochastic activation and exhaustion of individual T cells. These limitations motivate the use of agent-based approaches in settings where cell-level diversity is a central feature of the system under study.

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{PhysiCell: A Continuous Mechanics-Based Cell Simulator}
\label{subsec:rw_physicell}
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

PhysiCell, introduced by Ghaffarizadeh et al.\ \cite{ghaffarizadeh2018}, is a widely adopted open-source framework for multicellular simulations. It represents each cell as an off-lattice agent governed by continuous mechanics: cells experience adhesive and repulsive forces, deform, and migrate through a continuous spatial domain. The framework couples these mechanical dynamics with diffusible chemical fields (oxygen, signaling molecules) solved on a regular mesh, and provides a BioFML-based interface for specifying cell phenotypes declaratively.

PhysiCell is well suited to problems where cell mechanics, deformation, and continuous spatial positioning are essential---for instance, modeling tumor spheroid compaction or cell migration through extracellular matrix. Its off-lattice formulation, however, introduces computational costs that scale with the fidelity of the mechanical solver, and the framework's architecture is primarily oriented toward biomechanical questions rather than detailed immunological signaling cascades. The present work adopts a discrete lattice-based ABM approach instead, which sacrifices sub-cellular mechanical resolution in exchange for the ability to represent a larger number of distinct immune cell types, explicit gene-level tumor heterogeneity, and metabolic competition on a shared glucose field. Where PhysiCell excels at biophysical realism at the cell-pair interaction scale, the model developed in this thesis prioritizes immunological breadth and population-level dynamics relevant to treatment response prediction.

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{HAL: Hybrid Automata Library}
\label{subsec:rw_hal}
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Hybrid Automata Library (HAL), described by Bravo et al.\ \cite{bravo2013}, provides a Java-based toolkit for constructing hybrid models that combine discrete agents on a lattice with continuous PDE layers for diffusible substances. HAL offers a flexible architecture in which on-lattice and off-lattice agents can coexist, and its PDE solvers handle reaction-diffusion dynamics for nutrients, drugs, and signaling molecules. The library has been applied to a range of cancer modeling problems, including studies of tumor-stroma interactions and evolutionary dynamics under therapy.

HAL shares several conceptual features with the present work, notably the coupling of discrete cellular agents with a continuous nutrient field. The key differences lie in the immune modeling granularity and the computational infrastructure. HAL models typically represent immune cells at a coarser level of abstraction, often grouping multiple immune subtypes into a single generic effector population. The present model, by contrast, distinguishes thirteen immune cell types with subtype-specific behavioral rules. Furthermore, HAL is a single-process Java library, whereas the Repast4Py framework used here provides native MPI-based parallelism, enabling parameter sweeps and larger spatial domains on high-performance computing infrastructure.

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Agent-Based Models of Cancer}
\label{subsec:rw_cancer_abms}
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Agent-based modeling has been applied to a variety of cancer types and biological questions. Norton et al.\ \cite{norton2019} developed an ABM for triple-negative breast cancer that incorporated tumor cell heterogeneity, immune cell infiltration, and checkpoint inhibitor therapy. Their model demonstrated that spatial patterns of immune infiltration---rather than aggregate immune cell counts alone---can determine whether immunotherapy achieves durable responses. This finding underscores the importance of spatial resolution in treatment modeling, a design principle shared by the present work.

Wang et al.\ \cite{wang2015} proposed a multiscale ABM that coupled intracellular signaling networks with cell-level decision rules and tissue-scale dynamics. By embedding simplified ordinary differential equation models of key signaling pathways within each agent, their framework captured cross-scale feedback between molecular events and emergent tissue behavior. The present model adopts an analogous multiscale philosophy, though the intracellular layer is realized through a 16-gene DNA system governing tumor cell phenotype rather than through explicit signaling pathway ODEs.

Anderson and Quaranta \cite{anderson2008} applied evolutionary game theory concepts within an agent-based framework to study how selective pressures from the microenvironment shape tumor heterogeneity over time. Their work highlighted the role of spatial structure in mediating competition between tumor subclones and demonstrated that evolutionary dynamics on a lattice differ qualitatively from those predicted by well-mixed models. The evolutionary perspective informs the design of the present model's mutation and selection mechanics, in which tumor cells with different genetic profiles compete for glucose and evade immune surveillance with varying degrees of success.

Collectively, these studies establish that agent-based approaches can capture phenomena---spatial immune patterning, multiscale feedback, evolutionary selection---that are difficult or impossible to represent in continuum frameworks. The present work builds on these foundations while targeting RCC specifically and incorporating a level of immune cell type diversity that exceeds most prior ABMs.

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{The Merelli et al.\ Mesa-Based RCC Model}
\label{subsec:rw_merelli}
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

The most direct predecessor of this thesis is the RCC agent-based model developed by Merelli et al.\ \cite{merelli2021}, implemented in the Mesa framework for Python-based ABM. Their model represented the RCC tumor microenvironment on a two-dimensional lattice populated by tumor cells and a simplified set of immune cell types. Tumor cells followed probabilistic proliferation and death rules, and immune cells migrated toward tumor regions and exerted cytotoxic effects upon contact. The model demonstrated that an ABM approach could reproduce qualitative features of RCC progression, including initial immune containment followed by eventual immune escape in untreated scenarios.

The present thesis extends the Merelli et al.\ model in five principal directions:

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
    \item \textbf{Repast4Py/MPI port.} The simulation engine has been re-implemented in the Repast4Py framework, replacing Mesa's single-threaded scheduler with MPI-based distributed execution. This architectural change enables parallel parameter sweeps and supports larger spatial domains without proportional increases in wall-clock time.

    \item \textbf{Continuous glucose field.} A diffusion-based glucose concentration layer has been added to the spatial environment. Tumor and immune cells consume glucose according to type-specific metabolic rates, and the resulting spatial gradients create zones of metabolic competition that influence both tumor growth and immune effector function, consistent with the Warburg effect dynamics described in Section~\ref{sec:bg_metabolism}.

    \item \textbf{16-gene DNA system.} Each tumor cell carries a simplified genome consisting of 16 binary gene loci governing phenotypic traits such as proliferation rate, immune evasion capacity, and metabolic preference. Mutations occur stochastically during cell division, generating intratumoral heterogeneity that evolves under selective pressure from the immune system and the metabolic environment.

    \item \textbf{Sex hormone modulation.} The model incorporates estrogen and testosterone signaling pathways that modulate both tumor cell behavior and immune cell function in a sex-dependent manner. This extension enables the investigation of sex-based differences in treatment response, a question of direct clinical relevance to the ARON-1 trial.

    \item \textbf{Bayesian optimization and ARON-1 validation.} Model calibration employs Bayesian optimization to systematically search the parameter space, and validation is performed against clinical endpoints from the ARON-1 study. This represents a shift from the qualitative plausibility assessment in the original Mesa model toward quantitative correspondence with patient-level outcome data.
\end{enumerate}

% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Comparative Summary}
\label{subsec:rw_comparison}
% ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Table~\ref{tab:framework_comparison} summarizes the key characteristics of the present model alongside the three most closely related frameworks and the direct predecessor model. The comparison highlights the trade-offs inherent in each approach: PhysiCell provides the highest spatial and mechanical fidelity but at the cost of immune modeling granularity; HAL offers flexible hybrid modeling but lacks native parallelism; the Merelli et al.\ model established the RCC ABM concept but with a reduced feature set. The present work occupies a distinct position in this landscape, prioritizing immunological detail, metabolic realism, and genetic heterogeneity within a scalable parallel framework.

