The review presented in this section situates the contributions of this thesis within the broader computational oncology literature. The following chapter describes the design and implementation of the model in detail, drawing on the theoretical foundations established in the preceding sections and addressing the gaps identified in the related work.

\begin{chaptersum}
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item ABM captures heterogeneity, spatial structure, and stochasticity that PDE models cannot
\item RCC immunology involves 13+ immune cell types with complex pro/anti-tumor interactions
\item Warburg effect creates metabolic competition between tumor and immune cells
\item This work extends prior ABMs with 18 agent types, glucose field, DNA system, and sex hormones
\end{itemize}
\end{chaptersum}